<font color="#FF0000">WE ADD TO THE TOTAL</font><br>
<tt>Sun Oct 19 23:32:31 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
John,<br><br>
You pose a heavy question, which takes a departure from the manner we have used to allow ourselves to let it go and get into ourselves.  So here goes.<br><br>
I have found the lessons learned have applied to all levels of our current existence.  We learned how to establish a vision of what we wanted to do, plan our actions, set objectives, assign responsibilities, and empower the individual to do his part.  The members acted as a team with no personal objectives in mind.  One cohesive unit dedicated to the final product.  The quality of the mission or accomplishment of the objective was directly related to the safety of the individual as well as the group.<br><br>
A good leader learned early that he must earn his teams respect to be successful.  Respect is not a privilege of rank but of the individual.  We learned to attend to the needs of the individual, which would add to the strength of the team.  A good team allowed no one to be the brunt of the teams despite.  The absolute understanding that each man was important let each of us learn to lay our lives on the line for a friend.  Some carried this to the war and some learned.  The value of a man was determined from his character, honesty, integrity, dedication and above all his honor.  All this was the part of the man, not of the warrior.  Being a Warrior was a learned skill, but the rest had to do with character.<br><br>
We learned that hard work usually achieved results.  Work ethic is something I see in the veteran and I employ numerous from all branches of the service.<br><br>
We learned that we can not push the man, but as required must pull the team.  Leading by example was the only accepted method.  Never ask a man to do something that you wouldn't do yourself.<br><br>
I have found these things support the issues of Total Quality Management.  ISO 9001 and efforts such as Malcolm Baldrige.  The dedication to quality work never let the team down.  The ability of the individual to work without regard for individual recognition.<br><br>
The serviceman, veteran, is an individual that has achieved what others are searching for.  Many times we fail, as does the uninformed to see the worth of these fine men.  I can assure you that the defense industry has not missed this fact and uses it to their advantage.  The service vet is also very loyal to a good employer.<br><br>
Well John if this is the direction you want to go I am ready.<br><br>

<p><code>-- Some of the best  (SW) </code><p>


